CFItems.fullStatement: Recount a personal experience, story, poem, or topic including details.
Select or create audio recordings and visual/tactile displays to emphasize specific points in a presentation.
Clearly retell a story, poem, or personal experience or recount a topic with supporting details.
Essential Elements for English Language Arts
Reading Foundational Skills - Print Concepts
Kindergarten
Demonstrate emerging understanding of the organization of print.
With guidance and support during shared reading, demonstrate understanding that books are read one page at a time from beginning to end.
Grade 1
Demonstrate emerging understanding of the organization of print.
Demonstrate understanding of the organization and basic features of print (e.g., left-to-right, top-to- bottom orientation of print, one-to- one correspondence between written and spoken word).
Reading Foundational Skills - Phonological Awareness
Kindergarten
Demonstrate emerging understanding of spoken words, syllables, and sounds (phonemes).
With guidance and support, recognize rhyming words.
With guidance and support, recognize the number of words in a spoken message.
With guidance and support, identify syllables in spoken words.
With guidance and support, identify single syllable spoken words with the same onset (beginning sound) as a familiar word.
With guidance and support, recognize the number of sounds in three-phoneme (consonant-vowel- consonant, or CVC) words
With guidance and support, recognize if words are minimal pairs
Grade 1
Demonstrate understanding of spoken words, syllables, and sounds (phonemes).
Recognize rhyming words.
With guidance and support, match orally presented segmented phonemes (e.g., C-A-T) to pictures or words illustrating the corresponding word.
Identify a single syllable spoken word with the same onset (beginning sound) as a familiar word.
Grade 2
Demonstrate understanding of spoken words, syllables, and sounds (phonemes).
Extend rhyming patterns
With guidance and support, add, delete and substitute individual sounds (phonemes) in simple, one- syllable words to make new words.
Reading Foundational Skills - Phonics & Word Recognition
Kindergarten
Demonstrate emerging awareness of print.
With guidance and support, recognize first letter of own name in print.
With guidance and support, recognize environmental print.
Grade 1
Demonstrate emerging letter and word identification skills.
Recognize and/or identify upper case letters of the alphabet.
With guidance and support, recognize familiar words that are used in everyday routines.
Grade 2
Demonstrate emerging use of letter-sound knowledge to read words.
Identify the lower case letters of the alphabet.
Identify letter sound correspondence for single consonants.
Grade 3
Use letter-sound knowledge to read words.
In context, demonstrate basic knowledge of letter-sound correspondences.
With models and supports, decode and encode, in the way the child is able, single syllable words with common spelling patterns (consonant-vowel- consonant [CVC] or high frequency rimes).
Recognize 40 or more written words.
Grade 4
Use letter-sound knowledge to read words.
Use linguistic context and letter- sound knowledge to identify unfamiliar words.
Decode and encode, in the way the child is able, single-syllable words with common spelling patterns (consonant-vowel-consonant [CVC] or high- frequency rimes).
Grade 5
Use letter-sound knowledge to read words.
Decode and encode common sight words and single syllable words.
Reading Foundational Skills - Fluency
Kindergarten
Engage in purposeful shared reading of familiar text.
Grade 1
Begin to attend to words in print.
Engage in sustained, independent study of books.
Participate in shared reading of a variety of reading materials reflecting a variety of text genres.
Grade 2
Attend to words in print.
Read familiar text comprised of known words.
With support, monitor for and identify errors that disrupt comprehension
Grade 3
Read words in text. Read familiar text comprised of known words.
With guidance and support, use features of print to identify or verbalize appropriate expression while reading familiar texts.
Use context to determine missing words that impede comprehension in familiar texts.
Grade 4
Read words in text. Read text comprised of familiar words with accuracy and understanding.
With decreasing support, use features of print to identify or verbalize appropriate expression while reading familiar texts.
Use letter-sound knowledge and context to support word recognition when reading.
Grade 5
Read words in text. Read text comprised of familiar words with accuracy and understanding.
Use features of print to identify or verbalize appropriate expression while reading familiar texts.
Use letter-sound knowledge and context to confirm or self-correct word recognition when reading.
Reading - Key Ideas & Details
Kindergarten
With guidance and support, identify details in familiar texts.(RI&RL)
With guidance and support, identify major events (RL) or the topic in a familiar text (RI).
With guidance and support, identify characters and settings (RL) or important details and events (RI) in familiar texts.
Grade 1
Identify details in familiar texts. (RI&RL)
With guidance and support, identify important details (RI) and recount major events (RL) in familiar texts.
Identify characters and settings (RL) or important details and events (RI) in familiar texts.
Grade 2
Given guidance and support, answer "who", "what" and "where" questions in familiar texts. (RI&RL)
Identify the topic of a text (RI) and use details to recount events from familiar stories (RL).
Identify the actions of characters (RL) or important details and events (RI) in familiar and unfamiliar texts.
Grade 3
Answer who and what questions to demonstrate understanding of details in a text. (RI&RL)
Identify details of a text. (RI&RL)
Identify the feelings of characters in a story. (RL) Order two events from a text as “first” and “next. (RI)
Grade 4
Identify explicit details in a text. (RI&RL)
Identify the theme or main idea from a text. (RI&RL)
Use details from the text to describe characters in the text. (RL) Identify an explicit detail that is related to an individual event, or idea in a text. (RI)
Grade 5
Identify explicit details in a text. (RI&RL)
Identify the theme or main idea from a text when it is not explicitly stated. (RI&RL)
Compare two characters in a familiar story. (RL) Compare two individuals, events or ideas in a text. (RI)
Grade 6
Determine what a text says explicitly as well as what simple inferences should be drawn. (RI&RL)
Determine details in a text that are related to the theme or main idea. (RI&RL)

In literary texts, identify how a character responds to a challenge in a text. (RL) In informational texts, identify a detail that elaborates upon individuals, events, or ideas introduced in a text. (RI)
Grade 7
Analyze text to identify where information is explicitly stated and where inferences must be drawn. (RI&RL)
Determine details in a text that are related to the theme or main idea and how it is developed over the course of a text. (RI&RL)
In literary texts determine how two or more story elements are related. (RL) In informational texts, identify how two individuals, events, or ideas are related. (RI)
Grade 8
Cite text to support inferences from text. (RI&RL)
Summarize a familiar text and determine details related to the theme or main idea. (RI&RL)
In literary texts, identify which incidents in a text lead to subsequent action. (RL) In informational texts, identify how two or more individuals, events, or ideas are related. (RI)
Grade 9-10
Determine which citations demonstrate what the text says explicitly as well as inferentially. (RI&RL)
Given the theme or central idea, recount related events and details (including character and setting details for literary texts). (RI&RL)
Determine logical connections between characters, individuals, ideas, or events in a text. (RI&RL)
Grade 11-12
Analyze a text to determine its meaning and cite textual evidence to support explicit and implicit understandings. (RI&RL)
Recount the main events or ideas of a text which are related to the theme or central idea. (RI&RL)
Determine how characters, individuals, settings, ideas, or events change over the course of the text. (RI&RL)
Reading - Craft & Structure
Kindergarten
With guidance and support, indicate when an unknown word is used in a text. (RI&RL)
With guidance and support, recognize familiar texts (e.g., storybooks, poems, informational texts) and locate the front cover of the book. (RI&RL)
With guidance and support, distinguish between words and illustrations/graphics in a text. (RI&RL)
Grade 1
With guidance and support, identify sensory or feeling words in a familiar text; ask the reader to explain the meaning of unknown words. (RI&RL)
With guidance and support, identify a text as telling a story or teaching facts (i.e., informational) and locate the front cover, back cover, and title page of the text. (RI&RL)
Distinguish between words and illustrations/graphics in a text. (RI&RL)
Grade 2
Use a text's structure (e.g., repetition, rhyming, etc.) to identify specific content, sensory, or feeling words that meaningfully relate to the text. (RI&RL)
Identify the beginning and end of a familiar sequential text (RL) or identify relevant graphics in an informational text (RI).
With guidance and support, identify words and graphic representations that connect to the point of view, topic, or important details of the text. (RI&RL)
Grade 3
Determine words and phrases that complete literal sentences in a text. (RI&RL)

With guidance and support, determine the beginning, middle, and end of a familiar story with a logical order (RL) and use text features including headings and key words to locate information in a text (RI).
Identify personal point of view about a text. (RI&RL)
Grade 4
Determine the meaning of words in a text. (RI&RL)
Identify elements that are characteristic of stories (RL) and informational texts (RI).

Identify the narrator of a story (RL); compare own experience to that described within the text. In informational text, compare and contrast a primary and secondary source on the same event or topic. (RI)
Grade 5
Determine the intended meaning of multimeaning and domain-specific words and phrases. (RI&RL)

With guidance and support, identify a story element that undergoes change from beginning to end (RL) and determine if a text tells about events, gives directions, or provides information on a topic (RI).
With guidance and support, determine the point of view of a narrator (RL); compare two texts on the same topic (RI).
Grade 6
Determine how word choice changes the meaning in a text. (RI&RL)
Given guidance and support determine the structure of a text (e.g., story, poem, drama, argument, directions, informational). (RI &RL)
With guidance and support, identify words or phrases in the text that describe or show the narrator, speaker, or author’s point of view. (RI&RL)
Grade 7
Determine how word choice changes the meaning in a text. (RI&RL)

Given guidance and support, compare the structure of two or more texts (e.g., stories, poems, dramas, argument, directions, informational) and determine how a fact, step, or event fits into the overall structure of the text. (RI&RL)
Identify words or phrases in the text that describe or show the narrator, speaker, or author’s point of view. (RI&RL)
Grade 8
Determine the connotative meanings of words and phrases in a text. (RI&RL)
Compare and contrast the structure of two or more texts (RL and RI) and use important details to identify the main idea in an informational text.
Determine the narrator, speaker, or author’s point of view and how it differs from the audience or reader. (RI&RL)
Grade 9-10
Determine the meaning of words and phrases as they are used in text, including common idioms, analogies, and figures of speech. (RI&RL)
Identify where a text deviates from a chronological presentation of events (RL) and locate sentences that support an author’s central idea or claim (RI).
Determine author’s point of view and compare with own point of view. (RI&RL)
Grade 11-12
Determine how words or phrases in a text, including words with multiple meanings and figurative language, impact the meaning. (RI&RL)
Use a text’s ending (e.g., story (RL)) or structure (e.g, informational (RI) and determine its impact on meaning of the text as a whole.
Determine author’s point of view and compare and contrast it with own point of view. (RI&RL)
Reading - Integration of Knowledge & Ideas
Kindergarten
With guidance and support, identify illustrations or objects/tactual information that go with the text. (RI&RL)
With guidance and support, identify points the author makes in text. (RI)
With guidance and support, match similar parts of two familiar texts, identifying the adventures or experiences of a character. (RI&RL)
Grade 1
Identify illustrations or objects/tactile information that go with the text. (RI&RL)
Identify points the author makes in familiar text. (RI)
With guidance and support, compare parts of two texts, identifying adventures or experiences of characters in a text as same or different. (RI&RL)
Grade 2
Identify illustrations or objects/tactile information in text that depict characters. (RI&RL)
Identify points the author makes in text. (RI)
Compare details in two texts; recognize that texts reflect one’s own and other’s culture. (RI&RL)
Grade 3
Identify parts of illustrations or tactual information that depict story elements. (RI&RL)
Identify two related points the author makes in text. (RI)
Identify similarities between two texts and recognize that texts reflect one's own and others' culture. (RI&RL)
Grade 4
Make connections between the text representation and a visual, tactual, or oral version of the text. (RI&RL)
Identify one or more reasons supporting a specific point in a text. (RI)
Identify similarities between two texts and recognize that texts reflect one's own and others' culture. (RI&RL)
Grade 5
Identify illustrations, tactual or multimedia elements that add to understanding of a text. (RI&RL)
Identify the relationship between a specific point and supporting reasons in a text. (RI)
Compare and contrast details gained from two texts and make connections to other texts, ideas, cultural perspectives, identities, eras, personal events, or situations. (RI&RL)
Grade 6
Find similarities in information presented in different media or formats as well as in text. (RI&RL)
Distinguish claims in a text supported by reason. (RI)
Compare and contrast how two texts describe details and make connections to other texts, ideas, cultural perspectives, identities, eras, or personal experiences. (RI&RL)
Grade 7
Compare a text to an audio, video, or multimedia version of the same text. (RI&RL)
Determine how a claim or reason fits into the overall structure of a text. (RI)
Compare and contrast how two texts describe details and make connections to other texts, ideas, cultural perspectives, identities, eras, or personal experiences. (RI&RL)
Grade 8
Compare and contrast a text version of a story, drama, or poem with an audio, video, or live version of the same text. (RI&RL)
Determine the argument made by an author in a text. (RI)

Compare and contrast themes, patterns of events, or characters across two or more texts and make connections to other texts, ideas, cultural perspectives, identities, eras, or personal experiences. (RI&RL)
Grade 9-10
Compare and contrast the representation of a subject or topic in two different formats. (RI&RL)
Determine how the specific claims support the argument made in a text. (RI)
Make informed judgements about text; make connections to other texts, ideas, cultural perspectives, identities, eras, and personal events or situations. (RI&RL)
Grade 11-12

Compare two or more interpretations (e.g., recorded or live production of a play or recorded novel or poetry) of a story, drama, or poem. (RL) Analyze information presented in different media on related topics to answer questions or solve problems. (RI)
Determine whether the claims and reasoning enhance the author’s argument in a text. (RI)
Evaluate the quality of texts; make connections to other texts, ideas, cultural perspectives, identities, eras, and personal events or situations. (RI&RL)
Text Types & Purposes
Kindergarten
With guidance and support, use drawing, dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high-stakes and low- stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing, dictation and/or drawing to compose:
Opinion pieces in which they state an opinion.
Informative/Explanatory text in which they provide some information about a predetermined or self chosen topic.
Convey events, real or imagined and narrate a single event or several loosely linked events.
With guidance and support, use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that uses words familiar to the student.
Grade 1
With guidance and support, use drawing, dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high-stakes and low- stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing, dictation and/or drawing to compose:
Opinion pieces in which they state an opinion.
Informative/Explanatory text in which they provide some information about a predetermined or self chosen topic.
Convey events, real or imagined and narrate a single event or several loosely linked events.
With guidance and support, use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that uses words familiar to the student.
Grade 2
With guidance and support, use drawing, dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high-stakes and low- stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing, dictation and/or drawing to compose:
Opinion pieces in which they state an opinion about a topic or text.
Informative/Explanatory text in which they provide at least 1 fact about a predetermined or self chosen topic.
Convey events, real or imagined and narrate a single event or several loosely linked events. Include some details regarding what happened.
With guidance and support, use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that uses words familiar to the student and temporal words to signal event order.
Grade 3
With guidance and support, use drawing, dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high-stakes and low-stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing, dictation and/or drawing to compose:
Opinion pieces in which they state an opinion about a topic or text and include at least one reason to support that opinion.
Informative/Explanatory text in which they provide at least 2 facts about a predetermined or self chosen topic.

Convey events, real or imagined and narrate a single event or several loosely linked events. Include some details regarding what happened and tell about the events in the order in which they occurred.

With guidance and support, use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that uses words familiar to the student, temporal words to signal event order, and a beginning, middle, and end.
Grade 4
With guidance and support, use drawing, dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high-stakes and low-stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing, dictation and/or drawing to compose:
Opinion pieces in which they state an opinion about a topic or text and include some reasons to support that opinion.
Informative/Explanatory text in which they introduce a topic and provide some facts, details, and/or multimedia content about a predetermined or self chosen topic.

Convey events, real or imagined and narrate a single event or several loosely linked events. Include some details regarding what happened and tell about the events in the order in which they occurred.

With guidance and support, use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that uses familiar words, transitions to link and build connections, temporal words to signal event order, and a beginning, middle, and end.
Grade 5
With guidance and support, use drawing, dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high-stakes and low-stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing, dictation and/or drawing to compose:
Opinion pieces in which they clearly state an opinion about a topic or text and include some reasons to support that opinion.
Informative/Explanatory text in which they introduce a topic and provide some facts, details, and/or multimedia content about a predetermined or self chosen topic.

Convey events, real or imagined and narrate a single event or several loosely linked events. Include some details regarding what happened and tell about the events in the order in which they occurred.

Use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that includes an introduction, body, and conclusion. uses familiar words, transitions to link and build connections, and temporal words to signal event order.
Grade 6
With guidance and support, use drawing, dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high-stakes and low- stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing and/or dictation to write in a variety of modes:
Write an argument with a clearly stated claim about a topic and include clear reasons to support that claim.
Write informative texts which introduce a topic and provide facts, details, and/or multimedia content to develop the topic.
Write narratives to convey events and experiences, real or imagined.
Include dialogue, details regarding what happened, and tell about the events in the order in which they occurred.

Use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that includes an introduction, body, and conclusion, uses words that convey specific details, transitions to link and build connections, and temporal words to signal event order.
Grade 7
With guidance and support, use drawing, dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high-stakes and low- stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing and/or dictation to write in a variety of modes:
Write an argument with a clearly stated claim about a topic and include clear reasons to support that claim.
Write informative texts which introduce a topic and provide facts, details, and/or multimedia content to develop the topic. Provide a concluding statement.
Write narratives to convey events and experiences, real or imagined. Include dialogue, details, and tell about the events in the order in which they occurred.

Use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that includes an introduction, body, and conclusion, uses words that convey specific details, transitions to link and build connections, and temporal words to signal event order.
Grade 8
With guidance and support, use drawing, dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high-stakes and low- stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing and/or dictation to write in a variety of modes:
Write an argument with a clearly stated claim about a topic and include clear reasons to support that claim. Organize reasons logically.
Write informative texts which introduce a topic and provide well chosen facts, details, and/or multimedia content to develop the topic. Provide a concluding statement.
Write narratives to convey events and experiences, real or imagined. Include dialogue, details, character descriptions, and tell about the events in the order in which they occurred.

Use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that includes an introduction, body, and conclusion, uses words that convey specific details, transitions to link and build connections, and temporal words to signal event order.
Grade 9-10
With guidance and support as needed, use dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high-stakes and low-stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing and/or dictation to write in a variety of modes:
Write an argument or literary analysis with a clearly stated claim and valid reasons to support the claim. Organize reasons logically and develop the claim fairly.

Write informative texts which introduce a topic and provide well chosen facts, details, and/or multimedia content to develop the topic and convey information clearly and accurately. Provide a concluding statement.
Write narratives to convey events and experiences, real or imagined. Include dialogue, relevant details, character descriptions, and tell about the events and in a logical sequence.

Use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that includes an introduction, body, and conclusion, uses words that convey specific details, transitions to link and build connections, and temporal words to signal event order.
Grade 11-12
With guidance and support as needed, use dictating, or writing to compose writing for a variety of high- stakes and low-stakes purposes.
With guidance and support, use writing and/or dictation to write in a variety of modes:
Write an argument or literary analysis with a clearly stated claim and valid and sufficient reasons to support the claim. Organize reasons logically and develop the claim fairly.

Write informative texts which introduce a topic and provide well chosen facts, details, quotes, and/or multimedia content to develop the topic and convey information clearly and accurately. Provide a concluding statement.
Write narratives to convey events and experiences, real or imagined. Include dialogue, relevant details, characterization, and tell about the events and in a logical sequence.

Use a combination of drawing, dictating and writing to create a text that includes an introduction, body, and conclusion, uses words that convey specific details, transitions to link and build connections, and temporal words to signal event order.
Production & Distribution of Writing
Kindergarten
With guidance and support from adults, add more information to their own drawing, dictation, or writing to strengthen it.

With guidance and support from adults, explore a variety of digital tools to produce individual or group writing. With guidance and support from adults, produce writing through printing (including letter- like marks or forming some printed letters).
Grade 1
With guidance and support from adults, add more information to their own drawing, dictation, or writing on a topic to strengthen it.

With guidance and support from adults, explore a variety of digital tools to produce individual or group writing. With guidance and support from adults, produce writing through printing (including letter- like marks or forming some printed letters).
Grade 2
With guidance and support from adults, focus their own drawing, dictation, or writing on a topic and add more details to strengthen their drawing, dictation, or writing as needed.

With guidance and support from adults and peers, use technology (including assistive technologies) to produce and publish writing. Learn to produce writing through printing (including forming upper and lower case letters).
Grade 3
With guidance and support, produce writing that is appropriate for an explicitly stated task, and expresses more than one idea.
With guidance and support from adults and peers, including questions or suggestions, revise their own writing, dictation, or pictures.
With guidance and support from adults, use digital tools to produce writing while interacting and collaborating with others. Learn to produce writing through printing.
Grade 4
With guidance and support, produce writing that is appropriate for an explicitly stated task or purpose, and expresses more than one idea.
With guidance and support from adults and peers, plan before writing and produce writing focused on the planned topic, and revise their own writing, dictation, or pictures.

With guidance and support from adults, use digital tools, including the Internet, to produce writing while interacting and collaborating with others. Learn to produce writing through printing and/or typing.
Grade 5
Produce writing that is appropriate for an explicitly stated task or purpose, and expresses more than one idea.
With guidance and support from adults and peers, plan before writing and produce writing focused on the planned topic, and revise their own writing, dictation, or pictures.

With guidance and support from adults, use digital tools, including the Internet, to produce writing while interacting and collaborating with others. Learn to produce writing through printing, cursive, and/or typing.
Grade 6
Produce writing that is appropriate for the task, purpose, or audience.
With guidance and support from adults and peers, plan before writing and produce writing focused on the planned topic, and revise and edit their own writing, dictation, or pictures.
Use digital tools, including the Internet, to produce and publish writing while interacting and collaborating with others. Produce writing through printing, cursive, and/or typing.
Grade 7
Independently and collaboratively produce writing that is appropriate for the task, purpose, or audience.
With guidance and support from adults and peers, plan before writing and produce writing focused on the planned topic, and revise and edit their own writing, dictation, or pictures.

Use technology, (including paper and pencil, internet, audio, visual, and/or other interactive formats) to produce writing to interact and collaborate with others. Produce writing through printing, cursive, and/or typing.
Grade 8
Independently and collaboratively produce writing that is appropriate for the task, purpose, or audience.
With guidance and support from adults and peers, plan before writing and produce writing focused on the planned topic, and revise and edit their own writing, dictation, or pictures.

Use technology,(including paper and pencil, internet, audio, visual, and/or other interactive formats) to produce writing to interact and collaborate with others. Produce writing through printing, cursive, and/or typing.
Grade 9-10
Produce writing that is appropriate for the task, purpose, and audience.

With guidance and support from adults and peers as needed, plan before writing, produce writing for a specific purpose and focused on a planned topic, and revise and edit their own writing, dictation, or pictures.

Make intentional decisions about technology use (including paper and pencil, internet, audio, visual, and/or other interactive formats) to produce, publish, and update individual or shared writing products. Proficiently produce writing through printing, cursive, and/or typing.
Grade 11-12
Produce clear and coherent writing that is appropriate to a particular task, purpose, and audience. Produce clear and coherent writing that is appropriate to a particular task, purpose, and audience.

With guidance and support from adults and peers as needed, plan before writing, produce writing for a specific purpose and focused on a planned topic, and revise and edit their own writing, dictation, or pictures.

Make intentional decisions about technology use (including paper and pencil, internet, audio, visual, and/or other interactive formats) to produce, publish, and update individual or shared writing products. Proficiently produce writing through printing, cursive, and/or typing.
Inquiry to Build & Present Knowledge
Kindergarten
With guidance and support, participate in shared inquiry and writing projects.
With guidance and support from adults, identify information, objects, or events that relate to personal experiences.
With guidance and support from adults, recall key details from literary or informational texts.
Grade 1
With guidance and support, participate in shared inquiry and writing projects.
With guidance and support from adults, identify information related to personal experiences and answer simple questions about those experiences.
With guidance and support from adults, recall key details from literary or informational texts.
Grade 2
With guidance and support, participate in shared and independent inquiry and writing projects.
Identify information related to personal experiences and answer simple questions about those experiences.
With guidance and support from adults, recall key details from literary or informational texts.
Grade 3
With guidance and support, identify information about a shared or independent inquiry topic.
Sort information on a topic or personal experience into two provided categories and write or draw about each one.
With guidance and support from adults, recall key details from literary or informational texts and generate reflection or inquiry questions based on a reading of a literary or informational text.
Grade 4
With guidance and support, identify information about two or more aspects of a shared or independent inquiry topic.
Recall and sort information from personal experiences or a topic into given categories and write or draw about each one.
With guidance and support from adults, recall key details from literary or informational texts to support reflection or inquiry questions based on a reading of a literary or informational text.
Grade 5
With guidance and support, identify information about two or more aspects of a shared or independent inquiry topic.
Recall relevant information from experiences or gather relevant information from print or digital sources, sort information into given categories, and write or draw about each one.
With guidance and support from adults, recall key details from literary or informational texts to support reflection or inquiry questions based on a reading of a literary or informational text.
Grade 6
With guidance and support, conduct short inquiry projects to answer a question.
Gather information about a given topic from multiple print or digital sources.
With guidance and support from adults, draw evidence from literary or informational texts to support reflection or inquiry questions based on a reading of a literary or informational text.
Grade 7
With guidance and support, conduct short inquiry projects to answer a question.
Identify quotes providing relevant information about a topic from multiple print or digital sources.
With guidance and support from adults, draw evidence from literary or informational texts to support reflection or inquiry questions based on a reading of a literary or informational text.
Grade 8
With guidance and support, conduct short inquiry projects to answer a question and generate additional questions for further research.
Select quotes providing relevant information about a topic from multiple print or digital sources.
With guidance and support from adults, draw evidence from literary or informational texts to support reflection or inquiry questions based on a reading of a literary or informational text.
Grade 9-10
With guidance and support as needed, conduct inquiry projects to answer a question or solve a problem.
Write answers to research questions by selecting relevant information from multiple resources.
With guidance and support from adults, draw evidence from literary or informational texts to support reflection, analysis or inquiry questions based on a reading of a literary or informational text.
Grade 11-12
With guidance and support as needed, conduct inquiry projects to answer a question or solve a problem using information from multiple sources.
Write answers to research questions by selecting relevant information from multiple resources.
With guidance and support from adults, draw evidence from literary or informational texts to support reflection, analysis or inquiry questions based on a reading of a literary or informational text.
Comprehension & Collaboration
Kindergarten
With guidance and support, participate in conversations with others.
Communicate directly with supportive adults or peers.
Participate in multiple-turn communication exchanges with support from adults.
Respond to questions about the topic or text.
Consider individual differences when communicating with others.
With guidance and support, demonstrate an emerging understanding of a familiar text read aloud or information presented orally or through other media by answering questions
Ask for help when needed.
Grade 1
